isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.57) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.27. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.28, p < .001, 95% CI [12.99, 14.07]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.39, p = 0.743, 95% CI [-0.90, 0.64]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.20, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.48, S.E. = 0.32, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.12, -1.85]; Std. beta = -0.57, 95% CI [-0.71, -0.42])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.67, S.E. = 0.56, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.77, -1.56]; Std. beta = -0.61, 95% CI [-0.86, -0.36])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.95, S.E. = 0.49, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.91, -1.99]; Std. beta = -0.67, 95% CI [-0.89, -0.45])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.52, S.E. = 0.80, p < .001, 95% CI [-5.09, -1.96]; Std. beta = -0.80, 95% CI [-1.16, -0.45])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
